{{Infobox U.S. Courts of Appeals case |Litigants=Chrapliwy v. Uniroyal |Court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit]] |CourtSeal= |ArgueDate=October 1, |ArgueYear=1981 |DecideDate=February 16, |DecideYear=1982 |FullName=Alta Chrapliwy, et al. v. Uniroyal Inc. |Citations=670 [[Federal Reporter|F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/670/760/118079/ 760]; 28 [[Bloomberg BNA|Fair Empl. Prac. Cas. (BNA)]] 19; 28 [[CCH (company)|Empl. Prac. Dec. (CCH)]] ¶ 32,459 |Prior=Award of attorney's fees to Plaintiff, 509 [[Federal Supplement|F. Supp.]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/509/442/1448733/ 442] ([[United States District Court for the Northern District of Indiana|N.D. Ind.]] 1981) |Subsequent=[[Certiorari|Cert.]] denied, 461 U.S. 956 (1983) |Holding=Reasonable attorney's fees are recoverable for time spent persuading the Federal Government to debar a defendant from its contracts when engaging in discriminatory practices. Reasonable attorney's fees are to be determined by the plaintiff's attorneys' rates, not by customary rates of attorneys in the locality in which the district court sits. Reasonable attorney's fees for risks of litigation and quality or representation are recoverable. |Judges=[[Walter J. Cummings, Jr.]], [[Thomas E. Fairchild]], [[Wesley E. Brown]] (Senior District Judge, [[United States District Court for the District of Kansas|D. Kan.]]) |Majority=Fairchild |JoinMajority=a unanimous court |LawsApplied=[[Civil Rights Act of 1964#Title_VII|Title VII]] of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]] }} '''''Chrapliwy v. Uniroyal, Inc.''''', 670 [[Federal Reporter|F.2d]] 760 ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit|7th Cir.]] 1982) is a [[US labor law]] decision of the U.S. Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals concerning the award of attorney's fees in a discrimination lawsuit. The facts of the case involved allegedly discriminatory practices in violation of [[Civil Rights Act of 1964#Title_VII|Title VII]] of the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]]. The litigants of the case settled in favor of the plaintiffs, but brought the issue of reasonable attorney's fees to the district court.
==Facts== [[Uniroyal]] allegedly maintained "a segregated hiring and [[seniority]] system at its [[Mishawaka, Indiana]] plant where women were heavily employed in the footwear production division, while other lines predominantly employed male employees." Alta Chrapliwy and other female workers filed charges against the company in a [[class action suit]] that was eventually settled in their favor after years of litigation.
